{
  "What is a physical quantity?": "",
  "An abstract concept with no measurement": "",
  "A property that can be measured with a number and a unit": "",
  "A mathematical constant": "",
  "A property that can only be observed": "",
  "A physical quantity is any property of a material or system that can be measured. It always includes both a number and a unit (e.g., 5 meters). A number without a unit has no physical meaning.": "",
  "How many SI base quantities are there?": "",
  "Five": "",
  "Ten": "",
  "Three": "",
  "Seven": "",
  "The SI system defines seven base quantities: length (m), mass (kg), time (s), electric current (A), temperature (K), amount of substance (mol), and luminous intensity (cd).": "",
  "What is the SI base unit for mass?": "",
  "Gram (g)": "",
  "Kilogram (kg)": "",
  "Pound (lb)": "",
  "Newton (N)": "",
  "The kilogram (kg) is the SI base unit for mass. The gram is a smaller unit derived from the kilogram, the pound is a non-SI unit, and the Newton is a unit of force.": "",
  "What is a derived quantity?": "",
  "A quantity formed by combining base quantities": "",
  "A quantity that cannot be measured": "",
  "A unit with no physical meaning": "",
  "A base unit of the SI system": "",
  "Derived quantities are formed by combining base quantities through multiplication or division. Examples include speed (m/s), force (kg*m/s^2 = N), and energy (kg*m^2/s^2 = J).": "",
  "What is the SI base unit for time?": "",
  "Minute (min)": "",
  "Millisecond (ms)": "",
  "Hour (hr)": "",
  "Second (s)": "",
  "The second (s) is the SI base unit for time. Minutes, hours, and milliseconds are all derived from the second but are not base units.": "",
  "What happens when you add two values with different units?": "",
  "The result takes the first unit": "",
  "The units cancel out": "",
  "You always get the larger unit": "",
  "The result is meaningless": "",
  "You cannot meaningfully add or subtract quantities with different units (e.g., meters + seconds). Both values must share the same unit before addition or subtraction can be performed.": "",
  "Which of the following is a derived unit?": "",
  "Meter (m)": "",
  "The Newton (N) is a derived unit equal to kg*m/s^2. The second, meter, and kilogram are all SI base units, not derived units.": "",
  "What is the SI base unit for length?": "",
  "Centimeter (cm)": "",
  "Kilometer (km)": "",
  "Millimeter (mm)": "",
  "The meter (m) is the SI base unit for length. Centimeters, kilometers, and millimeters are all derived from the meter using SI prefixes.": "",
  "Which of the following is a base quantity in the SI system?": "",
  "Acceleration": "",
  "Applied force": "",
  "Kinetic energy": "",
  "Electric current": "",
  "Electric current (measured in amperes, A) is one of the seven SI base quantities. Speed, force, and energy are all derived quantities formed from combinations of base quantities.": "",
  "What is the SI base unit for temperature?": "",
  "Celsius (°C)": "",
  "Kelvin (K)": "",
  "Fahrenheit (°F)": "",
  "Rankine (°R)": "",
  "The Kelvin (K) is the SI base unit for temperature. Celsius and Fahrenheit are commonly used but are not SI base units. The Kelvin scale starts at absolute zero.": "",
  "What is a base quantity?": "",
  "A quantity created by combining other quantities together": "",
  "A fundamental quantity that cannot be expressed in terms of other quantities": "",
  "A quantity that only exists in theoretical physics equations": "",
  "A quantity that is always measured using digital instruments": "",
  "A base quantity is a fundamental physical quantity that is defined independently and cannot be expressed as a combination of other quantities. The SI system has seven base quantities.": "",
  "What does the term 'unit' mean in physics?": "",
  "A standard reference used to express the size of a measurement": "",
  "The numerical value obtained from a single experiment trial": "",
  "A category used to group different types of physical forces": "",
  "A formula that relates two or more physical measurements": "",
  "A unit is a defined standard of measurement used to express the magnitude of a physical quantity. For example, the meter is the unit for length and the kilogram is the unit for mass.": "",
  "What is meant by 'measurement' in physics?": "",
  "The process of comparing a physical quantity to a standard unit": "",
  "The process of converting one type of energy to another type": "",
  "The process of predicting the outcome of physics experiments": "",
  "The process of creating new SI base units from old ones": "",
  "Measurement is the process of comparing a physical quantity to a known standard unit to determine its value. Every measurement produces a number paired with a unit.": "",
  "Define 'derived unit' in your own terms.": "",
  "A unit that exists only in the metric system of measurement": "",
  "A unit built from combinations of base units through math operations": "",
  "A unit that scientists have agreed to stop using officially": "",
  "A unit that measures only very small atomic-scale quantities": "",
  "A derived unit is formed by combining SI base units through multiplication, division, or raising to a power. For example, the Newton (kg*m/s^2) combines kilogram, meter, and second.": "",
  "What is the difference between a 'quantity' and a 'unit'?": "",
  "They are two different names for exactly the same concept": "",
  "A quantity is what you measure; a unit is the standard you measure it in": "",
  "A quantity refers to large values; a unit refers to small values": "",
  "A quantity can be negative; a unit is always a positive number": "",
  "A quantity is the physical property being measured (e.g., length, mass, time), while a unit is the standard used to express that measurement (e.g., meter, kilogram, second).": "",
  "What does 'SI' stand for in the SI system of units?": "",
  "Scientific Investigation": "",
  "Standard Instruments": "",
  "Systeme International (International System)": "",
  "Scaled Increments": "",
  "SI stands for Systeme International d'Unites, which is French for International System of Units. It is the globally accepted standard for scientific measurement.": "",
  "What does the term 'magnitude' mean when describing a physical quantity?": "",
  "The direction in which the quantity is pointing or acting": "",
  "The numerical size or amount of the quantity being described": "",
  "The instrument that was used to perform the measurement": "",
  "The number of decimal places shown in the measurement value": "",
  "Magnitude refers to the numerical size or amount of a physical quantity, without regard to direction. For example, in '5 meters north,' the magnitude is 5 meters.": "",
  "What is the term for the SI base unit of electric current?": "",
  "Volt (V)": "",
  "Watt (W)": "",
  "Ampere (A)": "",
  "Ohm (Omega)": "",
  "The ampere (A) is the SI base unit for electric current. The volt, watt, and ohm are derived units used in electricity but are not base units.": "",
  "What is the meaning of the term 'luminous intensity'?": "",
  "The total energy output of a heat-producing light source": "",
  "The measure of how bright a light source appears in a given direction": "",
  "The speed at which light travels through a transparent material": "",
  "The number of colors visible when white light is separated": "",
  "Luminous intensity is one of the seven SI base quantities. It measures how much visible light a source emits in a particular direction, and its SI unit is the candela (cd).": "",
  "What is the term for a quantity like speed that is formed from base quantities?": "",
  "A fundamental quantity": "",
  "A compound quantity": "",
  "A derived quantity": "",
  "An independent quantity": "",
  "Speed is a derived quantity because it is defined as distance divided by time (m/s), combining the base quantities of length and time. All quantities that are not base quantities are called derived quantities.": "",
  "A student measures the length of a table and records '1.5.' Their teacher says the answer is incomplete. What is missing?": "",
  "The measurement needs more decimal places to be valid": "",
  "The measurement is missing a unit such as meters or centimeters": "",
  "The measurement should be written using scientific notation": "",
  "The measurement needs the name of the measuring instrument": "",
  "A physical quantity must always include both a numerical value and a unit. Writing '1.5' alone has no physical meaning because we do not know whether it refers to meters, feet, or any other unit.": "",
  "In a lab, a student calculates the area of a rectangle by multiplying length (in meters) by width (in meters). What unit does the area have?": "",
  "Meters (m)": "",
  "Square meters (m^2)": "",
  "Cubic meters (m^3)": "",
  "Meters per second (m/s)": "",
  "When you multiply two lengths measured in meters, the units also multiply: m * m = m^2 (square meters). Area is a derived quantity formed from the base quantity of length.": "",
  "A student tries to add 5 kilograms and 3 meters together. Why is this calculation invalid?": "",
  "You can only add quantities that share the same units or dimensions": "",
  "You can only add numbers that are both greater than ten": "",
  "You can only add measurements taken with the same instrument": "",
  "You can only add quantities that were measured at the same time": "",
  "Addition and subtraction require that both quantities have the same dimensions and units. Mass (kg) and length (m) are fundamentally different quantities and cannot be added together.": "",
  "A scientist measures how fast a car is moving and records the result in m/s. Is speed a base or derived quantity?": "",
  "It is a base quantity because it is commonly used everywhere": "",
  "It is a derived quantity because m/s combines length and time": "",
  "It is a base quantity because it only involves one measurement": "",
  "It is neither a base nor a derived quantity in the SI system": "",
  "Speed (m/s) is a derived quantity because it is formed by dividing the base quantity length (m) by the base quantity time (s). Any quantity built from base quantities is derived.": "",
  "A lab group needs to measure the volume of a box. Which base quantity do they need to measure three times?": "",
  "Mass": "",
  "Time": "",
  "Temperature": "",
  "Length": "",
  "Volume equals length times width times height, all three of which are measurements of the base quantity length. The resulting unit is m^3 (cubic meters).": "",
