  "Energy (Joule = kg*m^2/s^2) and force (Newton = kg*m/s^2) are different derived quantities with different units. Energy equals force times distance, so it has an extra factor of meters.": "",
  "A student measures the mass of a rock as 2 kg and its volume as 0.001 m^3. What derived quantity can they calculate?": "",
  "Acceleration of the rock": "",
  "Density of the rock": "",
  "Temperature of the rock": "",
  "Velocity of the rock": "",
  "Density is a derived quantity equal to mass divided by volume (kg/m^3). With 2 kg and 0.001 m^3, the density is 2000 kg/m^3. You cannot find acceleration, temperature, or velocity from mass and volume alone.": "",
  "A runner completes a 400-meter lap in 50 seconds. A friend says the runner's speed is '8.' Why is this answer incomplete?": "",
  "The answer should be written as a fraction, not a whole number": "",
  "The answer needs a unit (m/s) to be a valid physical quantity": "",
  "The answer needs to be converted to kilometers per hour first": "",
  "The answer is wrong because 400 divided by 50 is not equal to 8": "",
  "Every physical quantity must have a number and a unit. The correct answer is 8 m/s (400 m / 50 s). Without the unit, we cannot tell if the speed is in m/s, km/h, or some other unit.": "",
  "In a science fair project, a student uses watts (W) to describe power output. Is the watt a base unit or a derived unit?": "",
  "It is a base unit because power is fundamental to physics": "",
  "It is a derived unit equal to kg*m^2/s^3": "",
  "It is a base unit because it has its own special name": "",
  "It is neither base nor derived; it belongs to a separate category": "",
  "The watt is a derived unit. Power = energy / time = (kg*m^2/s^2) / s = kg*m^2/s^3. Even though it has a special name (watt), it is still built from the base units kilogram, meter, and second.": ""
